<subSubSection pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="92.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,332,357]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Etymology.</emphasis>
Species named after the variation in body colour observed between specimens, from light brown to almost yellow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="92" pageNumber="93" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="92.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,404,429]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[342,602,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicolor">
<emphasis box="[342,602,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Holopothrips varicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is remarkable for its light-coloured body (
<figureCitation box="[1079,1177,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 276–283" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 276–283. Holopothrips varicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (276) body; (277) head and pronotum; (278) prosternum, showing weakly defined basantra (white arrows); (279) mesonotum; (280) pelta; (281) metanotum; (282) pore plates on abdominal sternites V–VIII; (283) spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445260/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 276</figureCitation>
), with some specimens looking almost yellow in transmitted light, and for the somewhat concentric pattern formed by the anteromedian reticles in the metanotum (
<figureCitation box="[467,569,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 276–283" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 276–283. Holopothrips varicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (276) body; (277) head and pronotum; (278) prosternum, showing weakly defined basantra (white arrows); (279) mesonotum; (280) pelta; (281) metanotum; (282) pore plates on abdominal sternites V–VIII; (283) spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445260/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 281</figureCitation>
). Other interesting traits are the lack of discal setae on the pronotum, the presence of weakly indicated prosternal basantra (
<figureCitation box="[718,818,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 276–283" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 276–283. Holopothrips varicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (276) body; (277) head and pronotum; (278) prosternum, showing weakly defined basantra (white arrows); (279) mesonotum; (280) pelta; (281) metanotum; (282) pore plates on abdominal sternites V–VIII; (283) spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445260/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 278</figureCitation>
), absence of the third WR on abdominal tergites II–III and females with an enlarged spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[657,758,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 276–283" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 276–283. Holopothrips varicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (276) body; (277) head and pronotum; (278) prosternum, showing weakly defined basantra (white arrows); (279) mesonotum; (280) pelta; (281) metanotum; (282) pore plates on abdominal sternites V–VIII; (283) spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445260/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 283</figureCitation>
). This species shares some similarities to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1244,1349,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maiae">
<emphasis box="[1244,1349,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">H. maiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spermathecus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">H. spermathecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of head and position of maxillary stylets, but differs in the metanotal sculpture (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 276–283" captionStartId="91.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@91.[203,1387,193,1934]" captionTargetPageId="91" captionText="FIGURES 276–283. Holopothrips varicolor sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (276) body; (277) head and pronotum; (278) prosternum, showing weakly defined basantra (white arrows); (279) mesonotum; (280) pelta; (281) metanotum; (282) pore plates on abdominal sternites V–VIII; (283) spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445260/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 281</figureCitation>
). The metanotal sculpture of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[544,687,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicolor">
<emphasis box="[544,687,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">H. varicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from species with mostly equiangular reticulation in the metanotum, such as 
<taxonomicName box="[387,549,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hambletoni">
<emphasis box="[387,549,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">H. hambletoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[591,729,657,680]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennatus">
<emphasis box="[591,729,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">H. pennatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in being formed by smaller reticles with not as well-defined contours. This thrips is known to induce leaf galls on 
<emphasis box="[767,1031,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Neomithrantes obscura</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1048,1116,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1630,1653]" captionTargetBox="[234,1352,184,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1352,183,1606]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (1) galls on Siphoneugena reitzii (by H. curiosus); (2) galls on Myrciaria floribunda (by H. spermathecus) (Photo: André Santana); (3) gall on Myrcia guianensis (by H. molzi); (4) gall on Myrcia retorta (by H. striatus); (5) gall on Myrcia sp. (by H. cardosoi) (Photo: João C. Cardoso); (6) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. conducans); (7) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. longisetus); (8) gall on Myrcia selloi (by H. acrioris); (9) galls on Neomitranthes obscura (by H. varicolor) (Photo: Sheila Carvalho-Fernandes)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445184/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation pageId="92" pageNumber="93" refId="ref58384" refString="Carvalho-Fernandes, S. P., Ascendino, S., Maia, V. C. &amp; Couri, M. S. (2016) Diversity of insect galls associated with coastal shrub vegetation in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 88 (3), 1407 - 1418. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / 0001 - 3765201620150658" type="journal article">
Carvalho-Fernandes 
<emphasis box="[1378,1436,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
